    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-01-20T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-01-20T06:00:00-05:00" n="527"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d527">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.6831/241: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-01-20T13:00:00+02:00"
                            >January 20, 1940—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 20—10:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>11. Complying with instruction No. 622 of September 28, 1939,<note n="94"
                        xml:id="d527fn94">
                        <ref target="frus1939v02#pg_603">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 603</ref>.</note> I laid before the
                    Under Secretary for Foreign Affairs and the Ministry of National Economy this
                    morning the Department’s views and proposals regarding the negotiation of a
                    possible trade agreement. Further talks which may be necessary to facilitate the
                    Greek Government reaching a decision regarding its readiness to negotiate can be
                    carried on directly with the Minister of National Economy. While of necessity
                    noncommittal at this stage, both Ministers appeared receptive to our advances
                    and the latter, especially, expressed a hopeful attitude.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
